Addition of NIT to the aqueous solution of the CNDs can cause quenching in fluorescence over a linear range (Fig. 6A). Quantitative determination of NIT content in capsules was achieved using different methods such as external standard and standard addition methods. A series of standard solutions were prepared using standard reference material, this was used to establish a calibration curve (Fig. 6B) by plotting the fluorescence intensity against concentration, the coefficient of determination (R2) was 0.9924. Lowest limit of detection was 1.4 μM (3Sd/slope), and lowest limit of quantification was 4.6 μM (10Sd/slope), where Sd is the standard deviation of the lowest concentration that had response to NIT by 10 replicates. Standard addition method was used to assay the content of NIT in capsules as shown in Table 1
                        , the recovery was 96.6% -103.3% and the relative standard deviation was 1.4–2.4 (n = 5). The results of the assay showed that the average active ingredient content weight of the capsules is 50.26 mg that stands for 100.53% which falls within the acceptable range of not less than 90% and not more than 110% according to BP [76]. The results are in high correlation with the stated content of the studied pharmaceutical product proving that the suggested procedure shows high recovery, accuracy and sensitivity. The current assay is based on simple and rapid analysis with reasonable LODs and high selectivity. Different methods from the literature were summarized and compared to the current method in terms of materials used, methodology, limit of detection, and linear range (Table 2
                        ).

Furthermore, the hepatic enzymes and renal constituent amounts in the groups that received the treatment were almost close to that of control animals without significant (P > 0.05) variations (Table 4
                        ). Additionally, we found ordinary amounts of total red blood cells (RBC), total white blood cells (WBC), haemoglobin (Hb), packed cell volume (PCV), and platelets (PLT) in the tested blood (Table 5
                        ). Thus, any degrees of anaemia, polycythemia, fluctuations in platelet level and WBC counts were not anticipated in the treated mice which are jointly suggestions of bone marrow destruction and intoxication.
